The new AttrDict

AttrDict is now an attribute-mapping that mirrors `dict` exactly (though it
does not subclass dict for complicated reasons).

code cleanup

Better programming through dynamic attributes

Instead of creating any attributes found in the dictionary, create them on the fly as they are accessed. Build time is cheap (potentially much cheaper than looping through a dictionary each time), and makes subclassing much simpler.

bugfix: USE ORGINAL MAPPING IF POSSIBLE

Lesson learned, if you don't use the supplied mapping as the underlying mapping, you do two horrible things:
	loop over a subdictionary every time you access it as an Arr
	prevent assignment like `mapping.foo.bar = 'baz'

That is a terrible thing to do, so DON'T DO IT. copy/deepcopy tests should ensure this functionality doesn't get broken in the future.
